## 2. Structural Formats: Custom Formulations vs. Speed-to-Market Control

When choosing your private label execution path, you must balance your desired level of product uniqueness against your available launching budget and timeline. Manufacturers offer two distinct foundational service models:

### Custom Formulation (OEM Model)

This framework is designed for brands looking to disrupt the market with a completely proprietary product. The manufacturer’s food scientists work alongside you to build a recipe from scratch—such as an alternative-flour keto cookie, a functional protein-infused snack, or a unique botanical flavor profile. While this route delivers total intellectual property ownership and a distinct market moat, it requires higher upfront R&D investments, extensive shelf-life testing, and larger initial Minimum Order Quantities (MOQs).

### Stock Formulation (White Label / ODM Model)

If your primary goal is rapid market entry and low financial exposure, white labeling is the ultimate strategy. Manufacturers maintain a catalog of pre-formulated, consumer-tested, and fully stabilized "control recipes" (such as a classic premium chocolate chip, double chocolate fudge, or oatmeal raisin). You simply select a proven base recipe, apply your custom branding and retail packaging design, and launch. This model completely bypasses R&D testing phases, features significantly lower MOQs, and slashes your time-to-market down to weeks.

